[With 74 diagnosed cases, there are certainly likely to be many more infections which are anicteric (not jaundiced) or totally asymptomatic. Of the 74 cases, 1 patient apparently developed a severe disease, likely what is called acute fulminant hepatitis. Not specific for type A hepatitis, it certainly occurs with hepatitis B and E as well as hepatitis B superinfected with type D (a defective virus that requires HBV to replicate). The risk of acute fulminant hepatitis, at least with types A and B is generally thought to be 1 in 1000. - Mod.LL

